The alternative release scenario associated with a release of flammable substances at the Lost Creek Compressor Station is a vapor cloud explosion (VCE) from a 2" flange leak for a minute before ignition resulting in 4,700 lbs to be released.  The maximum distance to the 1-psi endpoint for this alternative scenario is <0.1 mile per RMP*Comp.  Although we have numerous controls to prevent such releases and to manage their consequences, no credit for passive mitigation measures was taken into  account in evaluating this alternative release scenario



General Accidental Release Prevention and Chemical-specific steps:

This facility was built in accordance with the appropriate mechanical and electrical codes for gas processing plants and is subject to OSHA's PSM program.  Written programs and procedures cover all of the key elements of the PSM program and the employees are well trained in the safe operation of this facility.



Chemical-specific steps Include:

1.  Hydrocarbon Detectors;

2.  Process Safety Relief Valves;

3.  Automated Plant Shutdown System.  The plant will be automatically shutdown should key process parameters vary from specified ranges;

4.  Manual valves to permit isolation of various portions of the process;

5.  Appropriately placed portable fire extinguishers to combat incipient stage fires;

6.  Back-up generator to keep controls powered during a power failure.



Five Year Accident History:

The Lost Creek Compressor Station was initially started in 2000.  The station has had no accidental releases that resulted in deaths, injuries, or significant property damage on site and no offsite deaths, injuries, evacuations, sheltering in place, property damage or environmental damage.



